The paper deals with the problem of estimating an unknown signal from noisy linear observations using a structure-inducing convex function. This is a common problem in signal processing and machine learning, which suggests cs.SP and cs.LG as likely categories. The paper also involves the analysis of the performance of the LASSO estimator, which is a popular method in compressed sensing and statistical learning, indicating cs.SP and cs.ST as possible categories. The use of Gaussian squared-distances and closed-form upper bounds suggests cs.NA and cs.SI as potential categories. Finally, the focus on the squared error and precise analysis aligns with the interests of the cs.IT community.
